snippet.textDisplay:
Wilder is overrated, no style or class about him. Throws punches like a windmill. Pretty sure thats not taught in most gyms. Honestly it's no wonder he doesnt look good in fights until he lands a bomb, very misleading.


Put him in against fighters from the 70's, 80's and 90's and he'd be shown up for what he is. Boxers back then could box and hit hard. Real hard hitters include Tyson, Foreman, Tua, Lewis, even further back Shavers, Joe Louis. These guys threw sledgehammers with accuracy rather than go full pelt for 5 wild punches in the hope one lands. If a Lennox Lewis type was around today he'd destroy Wilder. If Fury can land better, harder shots like he's training for then my money is on him.

snippet.textDisplay:
My money is on Tyson & my reasons are this:-


1, He's been knocked down & got back up so he knows he can take it.
2, He schooled Wylder for 11 out of 12 rounds last time when he wasn't in prime shape & is in far better shape now.
3, After he was knocked down in the 12th & got his head together, he went after Wylder & very nearly knocked Wylder out & probably still won the round in the end although I concede it was probs given as a 10-8 to Deontay.
4, Tyson is a far better boxer than Wylder.


So, I think Tyson will win, most likely on points but it wouldn't surprise me if he knocks Deontay out. I think what happened in the 12th last time will only give him more confidence as he knows he can take it from Wylder & that he has the ability to hurt him. He also probs doesn't want to leave it in the hands of the judges so I think TKO in either round 10 or 11.

snippet.textDisplay:
The outcome all depends on how much Fury has left in the tank. He’s clearly in decline. His hands and feet are a shade slower since he comeback and his legs are going. He’s improved his head movement to try to compensate for this. The Wallin fight showed clear signs of deterioration. I think the cut he suffered in that fight could be crucial here. I don’t think he’s given it enough time to heal. Hopefully Fury has enough left to outbox Wilder and win on points but does he have enough left in the tank? Will the scar tissue on his eye open up?

Wilder can be outboxed easily because he can’t box but Fury’s legs are going and that increases the likelihood that Wilder catches him.

I go for Fury on points even though I feel he’s in decline.

snippet.textDisplay: Wilder is not the hardest puncher in boxing history. That title has to go to Earnie Shavers. I actually think allot of heavyweights hit harder than Wilder. It is the punches you don't see that knocks you out, not necessarily the hard ones. He has a fast and precise right hand, that catches people of guard. Real hard punches like Foreman, Shavers, Liston, Lewis, the Klitschkos, etc. Have allot more TKOs than KOs, because hard punchers TKO people, while precise and fast punchers KO people.
